      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Selling a Brisbane home with young children: managing inspections, open homes, and routine disruption
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Selling with young children adds substantial logistical complexity. Good planning reduces stress without compromising the sale outcome. Here is the practical playbook.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Selling a family home is logistically demanding even without small children in the mix. Add toddlers, sleep schedules, school runs, and Saturday morning open homes, and the campaign period can feel like a series of staged disruptions to family life. The good news is that the demands are predictable, and a small amount of planning takes most of the friction out of the process.</p>

      <p>This article covers the open home routine, the night-before preparation, where to go during inspections, the toy and clutter strategy, bedroom presentation, the safety questions, the school timing complication, what to communicate to the agent, and how to keep both parents on the same page. It is written for the parents who would rather not be making it up as they go.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The open home day routine</h2>
      <p>Open homes in Brisbane are typically scheduled for Saturday mornings, with an occasional second weekday inspection during a strong campaign. Plan for the family to be out of the home for 60 to 90 minutes around the inspection time. Young children should not be present during the inspection itself. The home needs to be presentation-ready 30 minutes before the scheduled start, which means the family departure window is tighter than parents often expect.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Night-before preparation</h2>
      <p>Friday evening is the make-or-break window. A 45-minute pre-clean on Friday night turns Saturday morning from chaotic to manageable:</p>
      <ul style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.6rem;padding-left:1.5rem;">
        <li>Tidy living areas and put toys away</li>
        <li>Load and run the dishwasher</li>
        <li>Vacuum high-traffic areas</li>
        <li>Make beds and fold visible washing</li>
        <li>Wipe kitchen and bathroom benches</li>
        <li>Prepare a short Saturday-morning checklist of what still needs doing (taking out bins, fresh towels, opening blinds)</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The aim is for Saturday morning to be a 20-minute final tidy, not an hour-long deep clean.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Saturday morning routine</h2>
      <p>Wake at the usual time but allow 2.5 to 3 hours from wake-up to the home being inspection-ready. The practical sequence:</p>
      <ul style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.6rem;padding-left:1.5rem;">
        <li>Feed the children at the usual time</li>
        <li>Get them dressed and out the door before the final tidy starts</li>
        <li>One parent leaves with the children; the other stays for the final tidy and styling pass</li>
        <li>Put fresh towels out, light a candle if you use them, open blinds, switch on lamps in darker rooms</li>
        <li>Lock the home, leave the key under the agreed arrangement, and join the rest of the family</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The 30 minutes before the agent arrives should be quiet, not frantic.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Where to go during open homes</h2>
      <p>Have two or three default options ready so the question is never being asked at 9.30am on Saturday:</p>
      <ul style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.6rem;padding-left:1.5rem;">
        <li>A local cafe with outdoor space (Bulimba's Oxford Street, Hawthorne's Riding Road, Camp Hill's Martha Street all work)</li>
        <li>A park or playground (Hawthorne Park, Whites Hill Reserve, Carindale Recreation Reserve)</li>
        <li>A library (the Bulimba and Carindale branches are good wet-weather options)</li>
        <li>A nearby shopping centre</li>
        <li>A grandparent's or family member's home</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Wet weather plans matter; plan B should not require uncovered outdoor space.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The toy and clutter strategy</h2>
      <p>Children come with stuff. The aim is not to hide that the home is family-occupied (buyers expect to see signs of life) but to prevent the volume of toys and craft from becoming visual noise:</p>
      <ul style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.6rem;padding-left:1.5rem;">
        <li>Rotate toys: keep a working set out and box up the rest in storage</li>
        <li>Decant child clutter into clear or attractive storage bins each evening</li>
        <li>Use baskets that buyers find aesthetically acceptable (natural fibre, neutral colours)</li>
        <li>Remove trampolines, large plastic outdoor toys, and cubby houses before listing photography is done</li>
        <li>Reduce visible art and craft to one curated wall, not every surface</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Bedroom presentation</h2>
      <p>Children's bedrooms should look loved-but-tidy. Buyers want to see how the space works, not how it currently lives. Practical steps:</p>
      <ul style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.6rem;padding-left:1.5rem;">
        <li>Make beds with simple, neutral bedding</li>
        <li>Minimise visible toys and books to a curated shelf</li>
        <li>Remove drawings, posters, and tape marks from walls if possible</li>
        <li>Clear surfaces; less is significantly more</li>
        <li>Open curtains fully to maximise natural light</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The safety question</h2>
      <p>Open homes legally allow strangers into your home. Most attendees are genuine buyers, but a small number are not. Sensible precautions:</p>
      <ul style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.6rem;padding-left:1.5rem;">
        <li>Remove medication, cleaning products, and sharp implements from accessible places before each inspection</li>
        <li>Ensure pool fences and child safety features are functional and visibly compliant</li>
        <li>Secure jewellery, cash, passports, and small electronics</li>
        <li>Remove sentimental or irreplaceable items from prominent display</li>
        <li>Confirm the agent's process for tracking who enters during the inspection</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The school timing complication</h2>
      <p>Mid-week inspections (private viewings, second inspections, building and pest, valuations) typically happen during business hours, which collides with school drop-off and pickup. The practical workarounds:</p>
      <ul style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.6rem;padding-left:1.5rem;">
        <li>Block out a recurring two-hour window the agent can rely on for mid-week inspections (for example, 9.30am to 11.30am after drop-off)</li>
        <li>If both parents work, arrange a trusted family member, neighbour, or au pair to coordinate access to the home</li>
        <li>Use a key safe so the agent can access the home without you being present</li>
        <li>Brief the children on what is happening so school pickup feels normal even if the home is being inspected as you arrive home</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Noise, tantrums, and the realities of family life</h2>
      <p>Children sometimes have meltdowns at inopportune times. Buyers with their own children typically empathise, and good agents brief inspectors that the home is family-occupied. Do not feel obligated to apologise for normal family life. Buyers are looking at the home, not auditing your parenting. A child crying in the background of a phone call with the agent is not the campaign-killing event it sometimes feels like.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to communicate to the agent</h2>
      <p>The agent does not need to know every detail of your domestic life, but they should know enough to schedule sensibly:</p>
      <ul style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.6rem;padding-left:1.5rem;">
        <li>The children's general schedule (sleep times, school times, after-school activities)</li>
        <li>Any specific times when open homes are not viable</li>
        <li>Any health, sensory, or routine considerations that affect inspection scheduling</li>
        <li>Your preferred notice period for mid-week inspections (24 hours is reasonable; same-day with two hours notice is sometimes necessary for serious buyers)</li>
        <li>How you would prefer to be contacted (phone vs message)</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What not to do</h2>
      <ul style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.6rem;padding-left:1.5rem;">
        <li>Do not stay in the home during inspections. Buyers feel uncomfortable and the agent cannot work effectively.</li>
        <li>Do not over-promise that the home will be 'show-ready' at all times. Be honest with the agent about the reality of family life so the schedule reflects what is actually achievable.</li>
        <li>Do not let inspection scheduling damage the children's wellbeing. If a request is unreasonable, negotiate alternative times. A serious buyer will accommodate sensible constraints.</li>
        <li>Do not deep-clean as theatre on inspection morning. The Friday-night routine is what protects Saturday calm.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Partner alignment</h2>
      <p>Selling with young children only works if both parents are aligned on the routine. Agree in advance on the open home process: who handles tidying, who handles the children, who manages the agent communications, what the Friday night routine looks like. Share the workload deliberately rather than assuming one partner will absorb it all. Disagreement on inspection-day execution is the most common source of stress in family-home campaigns, and it is almost entirely preventable with one 30-minute conversation before the listing goes live.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical framework</h2>
      <p>Selling with young children is more demanding than selling without, but it is entirely manageable. System, routine, and partner cooperation produce smooth campaigns. Honest communication with the agent prevents inspection-day surprises. The aim is not to hide that children live in the home; the aim is to present the home well enough that buyers can imagine their own family in it.</p>

